at age 4 there wouldn't be the option to wait. &#10;All I am stating is that there are reasons people choose to start their child in KG after they have turned 5 or 6 and not all parents are out to get the younger kids. It had absolutely zero effect on our decision. Most people who voiced their feelings about having started school at 4 told us AFTER we told them that our DS was starting school at almost 6. It is not &quot;holding them back&quot; to not jump at the first moment we could possibly ship our child off to school. &#10;It is not illegal to start a child in school at age 5 or even age 6, so why is there so much hostility from the parents who choose to start their children at age 4. I personally find age 4 to be very young to start school, but as I have said, if the child is going to be in daycare or preschool during those times anyway it does make sense to start them in kindergarten. Otherwise it doesn't make sense. Regardless of when they start school they will be edcuated for 13 years of their lives. Why do parents feel the need to push other parents to start their children younger? "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="1375" language="en" documentId="5176" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="LittleMissMartha" date="04/04/2012" docType="forumpost" origUrl="http://community.babycenter.com/post/a32503567/yet_another_redshirting_debate?cpg=14" topic="redshirting" thumbsUp="0" thumbsDown="0" origId="5176" notes="" title="Yet another redshirting debate"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="11"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="43" sofa="1" begin="12" end="330"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="47" sofa="1" begin="331" end="798"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="51" sofa="1" begin="799" end="1375"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39 43 47 51"/></xmi:XMI>